\section{roctx}
\label{\detokenize{driver:roctx}}
\sphinxAtStartPar
Provides marker information for each operation, allowing MIGraphX to be used with \sphinxhref{https://rocmdocs.amd.com/en/latest/ROCm\_Tools/ROCm-Tools.html}{rocprof} for performance analysis.
This allows user to get GPU\sphinxhyphen{}level kernel timing information.
An example command line combined with rocprof for tracing purposes is given below:

\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
/opt/rocm/bin/rocprof\PYG{+w}{ }\PYGZhy{}\PYGZhy{}hip\PYGZhy{}trace\PYG{+w}{ }\PYGZhy{}\PYGZhy{}roctx\PYGZhy{}trace\PYG{+w}{ }\PYGZhy{}\PYGZhy{}flush\PYGZhy{}rate\PYG{+w}{ }1ms\PYG{+w}{ }\PYGZhy{}\PYGZhy{}timestamp\PYG{+w}{ }on\PYG{+w}{ }\PYGZhy{}d\PYG{+w}{ }\PYGZlt{}OUTPUT\PYGZus{}PATH\PYGZgt{}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYGZhy{}\PYGZhy{}obj\PYGZhy{}tracking\PYG{+w}{ }on\PYG{+w}{ }/opt/rocm/bin/migraphx\PYGZhy{}driver\PYG{+w}{ }roctx\PYG{+w}{ }\PYGZlt{}ONNX\PYGZus{}FILE\PYGZgt{}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYGZlt{}MIGRAPHX\PYGZus{}OPTIONS\PYGZgt{}
\end{sphinxVerbatim}

\sphinxAtStartPar
After \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{rocprof}} is run, the output directory will contain trace information for HIP, HCC and ROCTX in seperate \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{.txt}} files.
To understand the interactions between API calls, it is recommended to utilize \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{roctx.py}} helper script as desribed in \DUrole{xref,std,std-ref}{dev/tools:rocTX} section.

\chapter{Contributor Guide}
\label{\detokenize{contributor_guide:contributor-guide}}\label{\detokenize{contributor_guide::doc}}

\section{MIGraphX Fundamentals}
\label{\detokenize{dev_intro:migraphx-fundamentals}}\label{\detokenize{dev_intro::doc}}
\sphinxAtStartPar
MIGraphX provides an optimized execution engine for deep learning neural networks.
We will cover some simple operations in the MIGraphX framework here.
For a quick start guide to using MIGraphX, look in the examples directory: \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{https://github.com/ROCmSoftwarePlatform/AMDMIGraphX/tree/develop/examples/migraphx}}.


\subsection{Location of the Examples}
\label{\detokenize{dev_intro:location-of-the-examples}}
\sphinxAtStartPar
The \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{ref\_dev\_examples.cpp}} can be found in the test directory (\sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{/test}}).
The executable file \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{test\_ref\_dev\_examples}} based on this file will be created in the \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{bin/}} of the build directory after running \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{make \sphinxhyphen{}j\$(nproc) test\_ref\_dev\_examples}}.
The executable will also be created when running \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{make \sphinxhyphen{}j\$(nproc) check}}, alongside with all the other tests.
Directions for building MIGraphX from source can be found in the main README file: \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{https://github.com/ROCmSoftwarePlatform/AMDMIGraphX\#readme}}.


\subsection{Adding Two Literals}
\label{\detokenize{dev_intro:adding-two-literals}}
\sphinxAtStartPar
A program is a collection of modules, which are collections of instructions to be executed when calling \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{eval}}.
Each instruction has an associated \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{operation}} which represents the computation to be performed by the instruction.

\sphinxAtStartPar
We start with a snippet of the simple \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{add\_two\_literals()}} function:

\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
\PYG{c+c1}{// create the program and get a pointer to the main module}
\PYG{n}{migraphx}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{n}{program}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{p}\PYG{p}{;}
\PYG{k}{auto}\PYG{o}{*}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{mm}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{o}{=}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{p}\PYG{p}{.}\PYG{n}{get\PYGZus{}main\PYGZus{}module}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{;}

\PYG{c+c1}{// add two literals to the program}
\PYG{k}{auto}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{one}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{o}{=}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{mm}\PYG{o}{\PYGZhy{}}\PYG{o}{\PYGZgt{}}\PYG{n}{add\PYGZus{}literal}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{l+m+mi}{1}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{;}
\PYG{k}{auto}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{two}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{o}{=}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{mm}\PYG{o}{\PYGZhy{}}\PYG{o}{\PYGZgt{}}\PYG{n}{add\PYGZus{}literal}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{l+m+mi}{2}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{;}

\PYG{c+c1}{// make the add operation between the two literals and add it to the program}
\PYG{n}{mm}\PYG{o}{\PYGZhy{}}\PYG{o}{\PYGZgt{}}\PYG{n}{add\PYGZus{}instruction}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{n}{migraphx}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{n}{make\PYGZus{}op}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{l+s}{add}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{,}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{one}\PYG{p}{,}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{two}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{;}

\PYG{c+c1}{// compile the program on the reference device}
\PYG{n}{p}\PYG{p}{.}\PYG{n}{compile}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{n}{migraphx}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{n}{ref}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{n}{target}\PYG{p}{\PYGZob{}}\PYG{p}{\PYGZcb{}}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{;}

\PYG{c+c1}{// evaulate the program and retreive the result}
\PYG{k}{auto}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{result}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{o}{=}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{p}\PYG{p}{.}\PYG{n}{eval}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{p}{\PYGZob{}}\PYG{p}{\PYGZcb{}}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{.}\PYG{n}{back}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{;}
\PYG{n}{std}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{n}{cout}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{o}{\PYGZlt{}}\PYG{o}{\PYGZlt{}}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{l+s}{add\PYGZus{}two\PYGZus{}literals: 1 + 2 = }\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{o}{\PYGZlt{}}\PYG{o}{\PYGZlt{}}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{result}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{o}{\PYGZlt{}}\PYG{o}{\PYGZlt{}}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{l+s+se}{\PYGZbs{}n}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{p}{;}
\end{sphinxVerbatim}

\sphinxAtStartPar
We start by creating a simple \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{migraphx::program}} object and then getting a pointer to the main module of it.
The program is a collection of \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{modules}} that start executing from the main module, so instructions are added to the modules rather than directly onto the program object.
We then use the \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{add\_literal}} function to add an instruction that stores the literal number \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{1}} while returning an \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{instruction\_ref}}.
The returned \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{instruction\_ref}} can be used in another instruction as an input.
We use the same \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{add\_literal}} function to add a \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{2}} to the program.
After creating the literals, we then create the instruction to add the numbers together.
This is done by using the \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{add\_instruction}} function with the \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{"add"}} \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{operation}} created by \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{make\_op}} along with the previous \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{add\_literal}} \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{instruction\_ref}} for the input arguments of the instruction.
Finally, we can run this \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{program}} by compiling it for the reference target (CPU) and then running it with \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{eval}}
The result is then retreived and printed to the console.

\sphinxAtStartPar
We can compile the program for the GPU as well, but the file will have to be moved to the \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{test/gpu/}} directory and the correct target must be included:

\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
\PYG{c+cp}{\PYGZsh{}}\PYG{c+cp}{include}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{c+cpf}{\PYGZlt{}migraphx/gpu/target.hpp\PYGZgt{}}
\end{sphinxVerbatim}


\subsection{Using Parameters}
\label{\detokenize{dev_intro:using-parameters}}
\sphinxAtStartPar
The previous program will always produce the same value of adding \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{1}} and \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{2}}.
In the next program we want to pass an input to a program and compute a value based on the input.
We can modify the program to take an input parameter \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{x}}, as seen in the \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{add\_parameter()}} function:

\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
\PYG{n}{migraphx}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{n}{program}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{p}\PYG{p}{;}
\PYG{k}{auto}\PYG{o}{*}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{mm}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{o}{=}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{p}\PYG{p}{.}\PYG{n}{get\PYGZus{}main\PYGZus{}module}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{;}
\PYG{n}{migraphx}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{n}{shape}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{s}\PYG{p}{\PYGZob{}}\PYG{n}{migraphx}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{n}{shape}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{n}{int32\PYGZus{}type}\PYG{p}{,}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{p}{\PYGZob{}}\PYG{l+m+mi}{1}\PYG{p}{\PYGZcb{}}\PYG{p}{\PYGZcb{}}\PYG{p}{;}

\PYG{c+c1}{// add a \PYGZdq{}x\PYGZdq{} parameter with the shape s}
\PYG{k}{auto}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{x}\PYG{+w}{   }\PYG{o}{=}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{mm}\PYG{o}{\PYGZhy{}}\PYG{o}{\PYGZgt{}}\PYG{n}{add\PYGZus{}parameter}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{l+s}{x}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{p}{,}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{s}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{;}
\PYG{k}{auto}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{two}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{o}{=}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{mm}\PYG{o}{\PYGZhy{}}\PYG{o}{\PYGZgt{}}\PYG{n}{add\PYGZus{}literal}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{l+m+mi}{2}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{;}

\PYG{c+c1}{// add the \PYGZdq{}add\PYGZdq{} instruction between the \PYGZdq{}x\PYGZdq{} parameter and \PYGZdq{}two\PYGZdq{} to the module}
\PYG{n}{mm}\PYG{o}{\PYGZhy{}}\PYG{o}{\PYGZgt{}}\PYG{n}{add\PYGZus{}instruction}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{n}{migraphx}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{n}{make\PYGZus{}op}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{l+s}{add}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{,}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{x}\PYG{p}{,}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{two}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{;}
\PYG{n}{p}\PYG{p}{.}\PYG{n}{compile}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{n}{migraphx}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{n}{ref}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{n}{target}\PYG{p}{\PYGZob{}}\PYG{p}{\PYGZcb{}}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{;}
\end{sphinxVerbatim}

\sphinxAtStartPar
This adds a parameter of type \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{int32}}, and compiles it for the CPU.
To run the program, we need to pass the parameter as a \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{parameter\_map}} when we call \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{eval}}.
We create the \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{parameter\_map}} by setting the \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{x}} key to an \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{argument}} object with an \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{int}} data type:

\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
\PYG{c+c1}{// create a parameter\PYGZus{}map object for passing a value to the \PYGZdq{}x\PYGZdq{} parameter}
\PYG{n}{std}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{n}{vector}\PYG{o}{\PYGZlt{}}\PYG{k+kt}{int}\PYG{o}{\PYGZgt{}}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{data}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{o}{=}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{p}{\PYGZob{}}\PYG{l+m+mi}{4}\PYG{p}{\PYGZcb{}}\PYG{p}{;}
\PYG{n}{migraphx}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{n}{parameter\PYGZus{}map}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{params}\PYG{p}{;}
\PYG{n}{params}\PYG{p}{[}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{l+s}{x}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{p}{]}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{o}{=}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{migraphx}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{n}{argument}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{n}{s}\PYG{p}{,}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{data}\PYG{p}{.}\PYG{n}{data}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{;}

\PYG{k}{auto}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{result}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{o}{=}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{p}\PYG{p}{.}\PYG{n}{eval}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{n}{params}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{.}\PYG{n}{back}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{;}
\PYG{n}{std}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{n}{cout}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{o}{\PYGZlt{}}\PYG{o}{\PYGZlt{}}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{l+s}{add\PYGZus{}parameters: 4 + 2 = }\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{o}{\PYGZlt{}}\PYG{o}{\PYGZlt{}}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{result}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{o}{\PYGZlt{}}\PYG{o}{\PYGZlt{}}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{l+s+se}{\PYGZbs{}n}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{p}{;}
\PYG{n}{EXPECT}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{n}{result}\PYG{p}{.}\PYG{n}{at}\PYG{o}{\PYGZlt{}}\PYG{k+kt}{int}\PYG{o}{\PYGZgt{}}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{o}{=}\PYG{o}{=}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{l+m+mi}{6}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{;}

\subsection{Handling Tensor Data}
\label{\detokenize{dev_intro:handling-tensor-data}}
\sphinxAtStartPar
In the previous examples we have only been dealing with scalars, but the \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{shape}} class can describe multi\sphinxhyphen{}dimensional tensors.
For example, we can compute a simple convolution:

\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
\PYG{n}{migraphx}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{n}{program}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{p}\PYG{p}{;}
\PYG{k}{auto}\PYG{o}{*}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{mm}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{o}{=}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{p}\PYG{p}{.}\PYG{n}{get\PYGZus{}main\PYGZus{}module}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{;}

\PYG{c+c1}{// create shape objects for the input tensor and weights}
\PYG{n}{migraphx}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{n}{shape}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{input\PYGZus{}shape}\PYG{p}{\PYGZob{}}\PYG{n}{migraphx}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{n}{shape}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{n}{float\PYGZus{}type}\PYG{p}{,}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{p}{\PYGZob{}}\PYG{l+m+mi}{2}\PYG{p}{,}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{l+m+mi}{3}\PYG{p}{,}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{l+m+mi}{4}\PYG{p}{,}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{l+m+mi}{4}\PYG{p}{\PYGZcb{}}\PYG{p}{\PYGZcb{}}\PYG{p}{;}
\PYG{n}{migraphx}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{n}{shape}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{weights\PYGZus{}shape}\PYG{p}{\PYGZob{}}\PYG{n}{migraphx}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{n}{shape}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{n}{float\PYGZus{}type}\PYG{p}{,}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{p}{\PYGZob{}}\PYG{l+m+mi}{3}\PYG{p}{,}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{l+m+mi}{3}\PYG{p}{,}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{l+m+mi}{3}\PYG{p}{,}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{l+m+mi}{3}\PYG{p}{\PYGZcb{}}\PYG{p}{\PYGZcb{}}\PYG{p}{;}

\PYG{c+c1}{// create the parameters and add the \PYGZdq{}convolution\PYGZdq{} operation to the module}
\PYG{k}{auto}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{input}\PYG{+w}{   }\PYG{o}{=}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{mm}\PYG{o}{\PYGZhy{}}\PYG{o}{\PYGZgt{}}\PYG{n}{add\PYGZus{}parameter}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{l+s}{X}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{p}{,}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{input\PYGZus{}shape}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{;}
\PYG{k}{auto}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{weights}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{o}{=}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{mm}\PYG{o}{\PYGZhy{}}\PYG{o}{\PYGZgt{}}\PYG{n}{add\PYGZus{}parameter}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{l+s}{W}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{p}{,}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{weights\PYGZus{}shape}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{;}
\PYG{n}{mm}\PYG{o}{\PYGZhy{}}\PYG{o}{\PYGZgt{}}\PYG{n}{add\PYGZus{}instruction}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{n}{migraphx}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{n}{make\PYGZus{}op}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{l+s}{convolution}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{p}{,}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{p}{\PYGZob{}}\PYG{p}{\PYGZob{}}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{l+s}{padding}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{p}{,}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{p}{\PYGZob{}}\PYG{l+m+mi}{1}\PYG{p}{,}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{l+m+mi}{1}\PYG{p}{\PYGZcb{}}\PYG{p}{\PYGZcb{}}\PYG{p}{,}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{p}{\PYGZob{}}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{l+s}{stride}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{p}{,}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{p}{\PYGZob{}}\PYG{l+m+mi}{2}\PYG{p}{,}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{l+m+mi}{2}\PYG{p}{\PYGZcb{}}\PYG{p}{\PYGZcb{}}\PYG{p}{\PYGZcb{}}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{,}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{input}\PYG{p}{,}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{weights}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{;}
\end{sphinxVerbatim}

\sphinxAtStartPar
Here we create two parameters for both the \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{input}} and \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{weights}}.
In the previous examples, we created simple literals, however, most programs will take data from allocated buffers (usually on the GPU).
In this case, we can create \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{argument}} objects directly from the pointers to the buffers:

\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
\PYG{c+c1}{// Compile the program}
\PYG{n}{p}\PYG{p}{.}\PYG{n}{compile}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{n}{migraphx}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{n}{ref}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{n}{target}\PYG{p}{\PYGZob{}}\PYG{p}{\PYGZcb{}}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{;}

\PYG{c+c1}{// Allocated buffers by the user}
\PYG{n}{std}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{n}{vector}\PYG{o}{\PYGZlt{}}\PYG{k+kt}{float}\PYG{o}{\PYGZgt{}}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{a}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{o}{=}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{p}{.}\PYG{p}{.}\PYG{p}{.}\PYG{p}{;}
\PYG{n}{std}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{n}{vector}\PYG{o}{\PYGZlt{}}\PYG{k+kt}{float}\PYG{o}{\PYGZgt{}}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{c}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{o}{=}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{p}{.}\PYG{p}{.}\PYG{p}{.}\PYG{p}{;}

\PYG{c+c1}{// Solution vector}
\PYG{n}{std}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{n}{vector}\PYG{o}{\PYGZlt{}}\PYG{k+kt}{float}\PYG{o}{\PYGZgt{}}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{sol}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{o}{=}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{p}{.}\PYG{p}{.}\PYG{p}{.}\PYG{p}{;}

\PYG{c+c1}{// Create the arguments in a parameter\PYGZus{}map}
\PYG{n}{migraphx}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{n}{parameter\PYGZus{}map}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{params}\PYG{p}{;}
\PYG{n}{params}\PYG{p}{[}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{l+s}{X}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{p}{]}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{o}{=}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{migraphx}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{n}{argument}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{n}{input\PYGZus{}shape}\PYG{p}{,}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{a}\PYG{p}{.}\PYG{n}{data}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{;}
\PYG{n}{params}\PYG{p}{[}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{l+s}{W}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{p}{]}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{o}{=}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{migraphx}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{n}{argument}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{n}{weights\PYGZus{}shape}\PYG{p}{,}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{c}\PYG{p}{.}\PYG{n}{data}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{;}

\PYG{c+c1}{// Evaluate and confirm the result}
\PYG{k}{auto}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{result}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{o}{=}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{p}\PYG{p}{.}\PYG{n}{eval}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{n}{params}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{.}\PYG{n}{back}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{;}
\PYG{n}{std}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{n}{vector}\PYG{o}{\PYGZlt{}}\PYG{k+kt}{float}\PYG{o}{\PYGZgt{}}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{results\PYGZus{}vector}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{l+m+mi}{64}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{;}
\PYG{n}{result}\PYG{p}{.}\PYG{n}{visit}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{p}{[}\PYG{o}{\PYGZam{}}\PYG{p}{]}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{k}{auto}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{output}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{p}{\PYGZob{}}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{results\PYGZus{}vector}\PYG{p}{.}\PYG{n}{assign}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{n}{output}\PYG{p}{.}\PYG{n}{begin}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{,}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{output}\PYG{p}{.}\PYG{n}{end}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{;}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{p}{\PYGZcb{}}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{;}

\PYG{n}{EXPECT}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{n}{migraphx}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{n}{verify\PYGZus{}range}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{n}{results\PYGZus{}vector}\PYG{p}{,}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{sol}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{;}
\end{sphinxVerbatim}

\sphinxAtStartPar
An \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{argument}} can handle memory buffers from either the GPU or the CPU.
By default when running the \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{program}}, buffers are allocated on the corresponding target.
When compiling for the CPU, the buffers by default will be allocated on the CPU.
When compiling for the GPU, the buffers by default will be allocated on the GPU.
With the option \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{offload\_copy=true}} set while compiling for the GPU, the buffers will be located on the CPU.


\subsection{Importing From ONNX}
\label{\detokenize{dev_intro:importing-from-onnx}}
\sphinxAtStartPar
A \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{program}} can be built directly from an onnx file using the MIGraphX ONNX parser.
This makes it easier to use neural networks directly from other frameworks.
In this case, there is an \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{parse\_onnx}} function:

\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]

\end{sphinxVerbatim}

\section{Matchers}
\label{\detokenize{dev/matchers:matchers}}\label{\detokenize{dev/matchers::doc}}

\subsection{Introduction}
\label{\detokenize{dev/matchers:introduction}}
\sphinxAtStartPar
The matchers provide a way compose several predicates together. Many of the matchers can be composed so that \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{m(m1, m2)}} will first check that \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{m}} matches and then it will check that \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{m1}} and \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{m2}} will match.

\sphinxAtStartPar
The most commonly\sphinxhyphen{}used matcher is the \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{name}} matcher. It will match the instruction that have the operator that is equal to the name specified:

\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
\PYG{k}{auto}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{match\PYGZus{}sum}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{o}{=}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{name}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{l+s}{sum}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{;}
\end{sphinxVerbatim}

\sphinxAtStartPar
This will find \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{sum}} operators. We can also find \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{sum}} operators which the output is \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{standard\_shape}}:
\begin{quote}

\sphinxAtStartPar
auto match\_sum = name(“sum”)(standard\_shape());
\end{quote}


\subsection{Arguments}
\label{\detokenize{dev/matchers:arguments}}
\sphinxAtStartPar
We also want to match arguments to the instructions as well. One way, is to match each argument using the \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{arg}} matcher:

\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
\PYG{k}{auto}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{match\PYGZus{}sum}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{o}{=}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{name}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{l+s}{sum}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{n}{arg}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{l+m+mi}{0}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{n}{name}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{l+s}{@literal}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{,}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{arg}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{l+m+mi}{1}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{n}{name}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{l+s}{@literal}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{;}
\end{sphinxVerbatim}

\sphinxAtStartPar
This will match a \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{sum}} operator with the two arguments that are literals. Of course, instead of writing \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{arg(0)}} and \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{arg(1)}} everytime, the \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{args}} matcher can be used:

\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
\PYG{k}{auto}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{match\PYGZus{}sum}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{o}{=}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{name}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{l+s}{sum}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{n}{args}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{n}{name}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{l+s}{@literal}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{,}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{name}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{l+s}{@literal}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{;}
\end{sphinxVerbatim}


\subsection{Binding}
\label{\detokenize{dev/matchers:binding}}
\sphinxAtStartPar
As we traverse through the instructions we may want reference some of the instructions we find along the way. We can do this by calling \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{.bind}}:

\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
\PYG{k}{auto}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{match\PYGZus{}sum}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{o}{=}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{name}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{l+s}{sum}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{n}{args}\PYG{p}{(}
\PYG{+w}{                                }\PYG{n}{name}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{l+s}{@literal}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{.}\PYG{n}{bind}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{l+s}{one}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{,}
\PYG{+w}{                                }\PYG{n}{name}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{l+s}{@literal}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{.}\PYG{n}{bind}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{l+s}{two}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{p}{)}
\PYG{+w}{                            }\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{.}\PYG{n}{bind}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{l+s}{sum}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{;}
\end{sphinxVerbatim}

\sphinxAtStartPar
This will associate the instruction to a name that can be read from the \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{matcher\_result}} when it matches.


\subsection{Finding matches}
\label{\detokenize{dev/matchers:finding-matches}}
\sphinxAtStartPar
Finally, when you want to use the matchers to find instructions a callback object can be written which has the matcher and an \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{apply}} function which will take the \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{matcher\_result}} when the match is found:

\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
\PYG{k}{struct}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n+nc}{match\PYGZus{}find\PYGZus{}sum}
\PYG{p}{\PYGZob{}}
\PYG{+w}{    }\PYG{k}{auto}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{matcher}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{k}{const}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{p}{\PYGZob{}}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{k}{return}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{name}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{l+s}{sum}\PYG{l+s}{\PYGZdq{}}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{;}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{p}{\PYGZcb{}}

\PYG{+w}{    }\PYG{k+kt}{void}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{apply}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{n}{program}\PYG{o}{\PYGZam{}}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{p}\PYG{p}{,}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{matcher\PYGZus{}result}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{r}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{k}{const}
\PYG{+w}{    }\PYG{p}{\PYGZob{}}
\PYG{+w}{        }\PYG{c+c1}{// Do something with the result}
\PYG{+w}{    }\PYG{p}{\PYGZcb{}}
\PYG{p}{\PYGZcb{}}\PYG{p}{;}

\PYG{n}{find\PYGZus{}matches}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{n}{prog}\PYG{p}{,}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{match\PYGZus{}find\PYGZus{}sum}\PYG{p}{\PYGZob{}}\PYG{p}{\PYGZcb{}}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{;}
\end{sphinxVerbatim}


\subsection{Creating matchers}
\label{\detokenize{dev/matchers:creating-matchers}}
\sphinxAtStartPar
There are several ways to create matchers. The macros \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{MIGRAPH\_BASIC\_MATCHER}} and \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{MIGRAPH\_PRED\_MATCHER}} help with creating matchers. For example, we can create a matcher for shapes that are broadcasted:

\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
\PYG{n}{MIGRAPH\PYGZus{}PRED\PYGZus{}MATCHER}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{n}{broadcasted\PYGZus{}shape}\PYG{p}{,}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{instruction\PYGZus{}ref}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{ins}\PYG{p}{)}
\PYG{p}{\PYGZob{}}
\PYG{+w}{    }\PYG{k}{return}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{ins}\PYG{o}{\PYGZhy{}}\PYG{o}{\PYGZgt{}}\PYG{n}{get\PYGZus{}shape}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{.}\PYG{n}{broadcasted}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{;}
\PYG{p}{\PYGZcb{}}
\end{sphinxVerbatim}

\sphinxAtStartPar
If we want parameters to the predicate, then we will need to use the \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{make\_basic\_pred\_matcher}} to create the matcher. For example, here is how we would create a matcher to check the number of dimensions of the shape:

\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
\PYG{k+kr}{inline}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{k}{auto}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{number\PYGZus{}of\PYGZus{}dims}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{n}{std}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{o}{:}\PYG{k+kt}{size\PYGZus{}t}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{n}\PYG{p}{)}
\PYG{p}{\PYGZob{}}
\PYG{+w}{    }\PYG{k}{return}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{make\PYGZus{}basic\PYGZus{}pred\PYGZus{}matcher}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{p}{[}\PYG{o}{=}\PYG{p}{]}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{n}{instruction\PYGZus{}ref}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{ins}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{p}{\PYGZob{}}
\PYG{+w}{        }\PYG{k}{return}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{ins}\PYG{o}{\PYGZhy{}}\PYG{o}{\PYGZgt{}}\PYG{n}{get\PYGZus{}shape}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{.}\PYG{n}{lens}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{.}\PYG{n}{size}\PYG{p}{(}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{o}{=}\PYG{o}{=}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{n}\PYG{p}{;}
\PYG{+w}{    }\PYG{p}{\PYGZcb{}}\PYG{p}{)}\PYG{p}{;}
\PYG{p}{\PYGZcb{}}
\end{sphinxVerbatim}


\section{Tools}
\label{\detokenize{dev/tools:tools}}\label{\detokenize{dev/tools::doc}}

\subsection{roctx.py}
\label{\detokenize{dev/tools:roctx-py}}
\sphinxAtStartPar
MIGraphX driver provides \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{roctx}} command which can be used with \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{rocprof}} binary to get marker timing information for each MIGraphX operator.
In order to help user to process timing information, rocTX helper script is provided at \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{tools/roctx.py}}.
The \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{roctx.py}} helper script provides two main functionality: \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{run}} and \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{parse}}. Available knobs and usage are given below:

\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
\PYG{n+nl}{Usage}\PYG{p}{:}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{roctx}\PYG{p}{.}\PYG{n}{py}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{p}{[}\PYG{o}{\PYGZhy{}}\PYG{n}{h}\PYG{p}{]}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{p}{[}\PYG{o}{\PYGZhy{}}\PYG{o}{\PYGZhy{}}\PYG{n}{json}\PYG{o}{\PYGZhy{}}\PYG{n}{path}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{json\PYGZus{}path}\PYG{p}{]}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{p}{[}\PYG{o}{\PYGZhy{}}\PYG{o}{\PYGZhy{}}\PYG{n}{out}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{out}\PYG{p}{]}
\PYG{p}{[}\PYG{o}{\PYGZhy{}}\PYG{o}{\PYGZhy{}}\PYG{n}{study}\PYG{o}{\PYGZhy{}}\PYG{n}{name}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{study}\PYG{o}{\PYGZhy{}}\PYG{n}{name}\PYG{p}{]}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{p}{[}\PYG{o}{\PYGZhy{}}\PYG{o}{\PYGZhy{}}\PYG{n}{repeat}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{n}{repeat}\PYG{p}{]}\PYG{+w}{ }\PYG{p}{[}\PYG{o}{\PYGZhy{}}\PYG{o}{\PYGZhy{}}\PYG{n}{parse}\PYG{p}{]}

\sphinxAtStartPar
Runs \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{migraphx\sphinxhyphen{}driver roctx}} command and given \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{migraphx\sphinxhyphen{}driver}} knobs, and then parses the results, providing GPU kernel timing information.
MIGraphX knobs can be given via a string to \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{\sphinxhyphen{}\sphinxhyphen{}run}} knob. Please see the examples below.
\index{command line option@\spxentry{command line option}!\sphinxhyphen{}\sphinxhyphen{}parse@\spxentry{\sphinxhyphen{}\sphinxhyphen{}parse}}\index{\sphinxhyphen{}\sphinxhyphen{}parse@\spxentry{\sphinxhyphen{}\sphinxhyphen{}parse}!command line option@\spxentry{command line option}}

\end{fulllineitems}


\sphinxAtStartPar
Given \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{\sphinxhyphen{}\sphinxhyphen{}json\sphinxhyphen{}path}}, parses JSON file and provides GPU kernel timing information.

\sphinxAtStartPar
Provides additional debug information related to data. Only use for debugging purposes.

\sphinxAtStartPar
\sphinxstylestrong{Examples:}

\sphinxAtStartPar
\sphinxstylestrong{Running inference with rocTX for a given ONNX file:}

\begin{sphinxVerbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
python roctx.py \PYGZhy{}\PYGZhy{}run \PYGZsq{}\PYGZhy{}\PYGZhy{}onnx \PYGZhy{}\PYGZhy{}gpu fcn\PYGZhy{}resnet50\PYGZhy{}11.onnx\PYGZsq{} \PYGZhy{}\PYGZhy{}out output\PYGZus{}folder \PYGZhy{}\PYGZhy{}repeat 5
\end{sphinxVerbatim}

\sphinxAtStartPar
After a run, similar to output given below is expected at terminal. The output will provide \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{SUM}}, \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{MIN}}, \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{MAX}} and \sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{COUNT}} information for each kernel executed for a given model.
Average total time is also provided. There are three files provided for reference:
\begin{enumerate}
\sphinxsetlistlabels{\arabic}{enumi}{enumii}{}{.}%
\item {} 
\sphinxAtStartPar
\sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{OUTPUT CSV FILE}} provides a summary of the run, providing utilized MIGraphX knobs and related kernel timing information

\item {} 
\sphinxAtStartPar
\sphinxcode{\sphinxupquote{KERNEL TIMING DETAILS}} provides the hotspot kernel timing information

\item {} 
\sphinxAtStartPar
This will provide all output data related to all iterations executed during a run.

\end{enumerate}

\sphinxAtStartPar

\sphinxAtStartPar

\noindent\sphinxincludegraphics{{roctx2}.jpg}

\end{sphinxVerbatim}
